WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
My piece is to be able to answer the question in regards to the role of the care partner

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:10.080
in optimizing patient outcomes for multiple myeloma.

00:00:10.740 --> 00:00:16.440
And what you see on this slide, it just highlights, again, my personal story in the fact that

00:00:16.440 --> 00:00:22.900
from a J&J perspective, as far as my husband being diagnosed with multiple myeloma and

00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:28.860
really being able to go through, again, the unknown about multiple myeloma, educating

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:36.500
myself, educating us, talking countless times with specialists in order to be able to understand

00:00:36.500 --> 00:00:43.080
what this disease is, because we were blindsided, and then being able, from a diagnostic perspective,

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:48.940
to really understand the diagnosis and then being able to make that decision for treatment,

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:54.380
which we had to do quite quickly, and then, of course, being able to live now with the

00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:55.960
impact of multiple myeloma.

00:00:56.780 --> 00:00:58.740
So that put me into an advocate.

00:00:58.860 --> 00:01:04.180
So I'm sharing with you here the slide that just highlights, again, it's just a snapshot.

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:11.120
I'm not going to go into details in regards to the overall care pattern, but just to have

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:18.420
you see here, snapshotly, we work quite aggressively in taking care of my husband and being able

00:01:18.420 --> 00:01:24.980
to navigate through nine different lines of treatment, all trying to find the best care

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:28.840
for him, the best treatment plan that will be able to put his disease at least in the

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:30.000
right place and to remission.

00:01:30.580 --> 00:01:38.580
I will want to acknowledge that this is 2020 into 2023, and it warms my heart to see the

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:41.680
medical advancement that has been able to take place.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:48.160
Once we started, we started with a triple induction therapy, and today, because of you

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:52.960
in this room, because of all of the research that you have done, we're now looking at quad

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:57.220
and being able to more aggressively go after that frontline treatment.

00:01:58.020 --> 00:01:58.740
Another great thing.

00:01:58.740 --> 00:01:58.840
Another great thing.

00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:01.740
Another great medical advancement is, you know, CAR-T.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:04.300
For us, CAR-T was our fourth line treatment.

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:07.900
Today, that has transitioned up to a second line treatment.

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:12.400
So all moving in the right direction, just based on the research of everyone in this

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:12.740
room.

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:14.000
So I do thank you.

00:02:14.940 --> 00:02:21.020
However, within the process, and we fight quite courageously in order to get the best

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:26.420
care, one of the things that I want to highlight as far as our challenge, we had access.

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:28.180
Access was not an issue.

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:28.740
But as I mentioned, we had access.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:34.220
I mentioned the late diagnosis and not having the value of having that pre-screening.

00:02:34.860 --> 00:02:40.200
When we got to, I'm based in Chicago, we're based in Chicago, and we were at a major cancer

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:42.780
center being able to seek care.

00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:48.940
But based on my connections, I was able to find out very late in the stage about an expanded

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:54.380
clinical trial, and that was taking place at Cleveland Clinic with Dr. Mazzanio.

00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:57.760
That's how I got connected from Chicago all the way to Cleveland.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:04.340
And that, even for me today, having that access, having that privilege to participate

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:10.340
into an expanded study that was not available in my area, brings me a great deal of peace

00:03:10.340 --> 00:03:13.000
right now in knowing, again, we sought the best care.

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:15.440
But this is not the case for everyone.

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:21.760
Folks are not able to travel even four miles, not four miles, four hours away to seek care.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:24.780
They're not able to get state to state to seek care.

00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:27.840
And this is what remains a burden on my heart.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:32.920
In order to, one, ensuring that there is access for others to be able to get treatment.

00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:38.140
So I really encouraged by the discussion as far as the community, being able to look at

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:44.320
the community approach and being able to bridge that gap to being sure that we're having care.

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:49.300
But also, I want you to think about across the line, across the state, that there may

00:03:49.300 --> 00:03:52.380
not be a certain clinical trial in your area.

00:03:52.380 --> 00:03:57.660
And really being able to consider the patient and trying to save that one patient life to

00:03:57.660 --> 00:04:02.780
be able to partner with another institution that may be in another state and then at least

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:03.920
make that as an option.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:08.280
So that was definitely a key learning that I do want to highlight.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:12.540
The second part is the opportunity, again, of data representation.

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:18.740
Unfortunately for us, with some of the drugs that we tried, there was not significant data

00:04:18.740 --> 00:04:26.880
that was represented that was able to really identify demographically what and how others,

00:04:27.060 --> 00:04:27.300
you know, I'm going to say, you know, you're going to be able to do that.

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:31.680
I'm going to say within the high-risk community responded to these treatment.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:38.020
So these were very difficult decisions that we had to make in order to, one, be able to,

00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:41.620
you know, seek care and be able to indulge in some of these trials.

00:04:41.940 --> 00:04:47.100
So I do encourage you as you're doing your research, please be able to identify and really

00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:53.100
think about all patients in mind and be able to document the different patients that are

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:57.100
able to be able to go through from a demographic perspective.

00:04:57.300 --> 00:04:59.220
To provide that opportunity.

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:02.060
For us, again, I remain at peace.

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:03.500
I remain grateful to Dr.

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:10.020
Mazanio because she established with us a trust, a trust that was there that I'm going to say at

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:12.660
the end of life, she was fighting for us.

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:15.560
And, you know, having that trust is quite important.

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:21.080
So spending that time with patients was quite significant to us.

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:26.160
She understood, you know, us personally, understood what we were getting to.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:27.280
And as I talk,

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:31.660
with more and more patients, there is not always that opportunity for trust,

00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:35.320
for building relationship with their oncology team,

00:05:35.480 --> 00:05:38.980
which really makes a difference in the overall care notion.

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:46.220
So as I close out us here today as to, you know, from a care partner perspective,

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:51.880
being able to, you know, get optimal care, optimal outcome for patients.

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:56.620
And of course, in this case, your loved ones, you know, really, again,

00:05:56.620 --> 00:05:57.220
being that.

00:05:57.300 --> 00:05:58.860
The patient is the voice for the voiceless.

00:05:58.860 --> 00:06:06.360
I always like to say the patient is the, the heart and the soul as to how we enable purpose driven

00:06:06.360 --> 00:06:11.700
mission to move forward, how we enable practice to move forward, but also including that care

00:06:11.700 --> 00:06:16.680
partner, because the care partner is the engine, right behind the scenes that are making the

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:23.720
calls, managing through this, navigating this disease to ensure that the patient is focused on,

00:06:23.800 --> 00:06:27.280
you know, one most important assignment, living and living through this.

00:06:27.300 --> 00:06:30.560
disease. So again, I do want to thank you for this opportunity.
